    },
    {
      "id": "LKWyeDRMZYad_14QXogYe",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 5956.651624094223,
      "y": -986.7910128779334,
      "width": 773.91943359375,
      "height": 550,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bBl",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1270477752,
      "version": 935,
      "versionNonce": 1049281736,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1770980712121,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Aim to migrate the most problematic components first. \n\nThe brief mentions:\n-  \"the whole site becomes unresponsive due to database load\"\n-  \"the job queue gets flooded with jobs that it cannot execute in time\"\n\nI would therefore start by migrating the database to AWS. \n\n1) Create a SQL db for stock management in AWS.\n2) Implement dual write functionality in Heroku app\n3) Implement read functionality in Heroku app from AWS\n4) Migrate the Data, during controlled downtime if necessary\n5) Turn off the writes and read to Heroku DB\n\nThis now unlocks creating the browse caches in dynamoDB in the AWS estate.\n\nI would either prioritise this work next, or the async order details processing, \ndepending on where the key bottlenecks now lie\n\n\n\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Aim to migrate the most problematic components first. \n\nThe brief mentions:\n-  \"the whole site becomes unresponsive due to database load\"\n-  \"the job queue gets flooded with jobs that it cannot execute in time\"\n\nI would therefore start by migrating the database to AWS. \n\n1) Create a SQL db for stock management in AWS.\n2) Implement dual write functionality in Heroku app\n3) Implement read functionality in Heroku app from AWS\n4) Migrate the Data, during controlled downtime if necessary\n5) Turn off the writes and read to Heroku DB\n\nThis now unlocks creating the browse caches in dynamoDB in the AWS estate.\n\nI would either prioritise this work next, or the async order details processing, \ndepending on where the key bottlenecks now lie\n\n\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
